"marriage","header":"Three Hart brothers each married a Hooker sister","body":"He was one of three sons of Capt. John Hart who each married a daughter of John Hooker Esq. of Farmington — Nathaniel married Abigail, Samuel married Mary, and Matthew married Sarah, between 1719 and 1725, binding two of Farmington's founding families."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Died when his only son was fourteen","body":"Lieut. Samuel Hart had planned a collegiate education for his only son Samuel, but died when the boy was about fourteen. His widow, unwilling to part with him, kept him home and provided the best education locally available."}],"baptism":{"year":1692,"month":9,"day":18,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"bio":{"title":"Lieutenant","display_name":"Lieut. Samuel Hart","first_name":"Samuel","last_name":"Hart","married_names":[]},"landmarks":[],"residence":{"city":"Berlin","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"samuel-hart-1692"},"H00100":{"id":"H00100","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":4,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1700,"month":7,"day":11,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1780,"month":11,"day":22,"city":"Worthington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00030","mother_id":"I00031"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00029","children_ids":["H00277","H00278","H00279","H00280","H00281"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1723,"date_month":12,"date_day":25,"location_country":"United States"}],"open_questions":[{"question":"Elihu Burritt descent through this line","status":"closed","notes":"CLOSED: Elihu Burritt's Hooker descent through this line is NOT CONFIRMED. His connection to the tree is through KINSHIP, not descent: his grandfather Elijah Hinsdale (X01931) and Lydia Hinsdale Hart (I00034) were siblings — both children of Capt. John Hinsdale (X00039). This makes Burritt the first cousin once removed of Emma Hart Willard (H00597) and Almira Hart Phelps (H00598). The claim that Burritt descended from Thomas Hooker through Huldah Hart (H00280) could not be traced through available sources. He is documented in the tree as an orbit_notable (X01932) with the Hinsdale kinship connection noted.","action":"No further action needed."}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 100"},{"short":"Phelps/NYGB 1843","full":"Mrs. Almira Hart Lincoln Phelps, article on Hart family, New York Genealogical and Biographical Record","url":"https://www.newyorkfamilyhistory.org/online-records/nygb-record/566-074/16","author":"Mrs. Almira Hart Lincoln Phelps (1793-1884), youngest daughter of Capt. Samuel Hart of Kensington, granddaughter of Lieut. Samuel Hart and Mary (Hooker) Hart"}],"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":null,"primary_url":null,"primary_url_label":null},"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"I00028","display_label":"Brother-in-law via Hart-Hooker triple marriage, 1719-1726","link_text":"Nathaniel Hart","notes":"One of the three Hart-Hooker marriages between 1719 and 1726: three daughters of Hon. John Hooker (H00030) married three sons of Capt. John Hart (X00033). Nathaniel Hart married Mary Hooker's sister Abigail Hooker (H00099) in 1719; Mary Hooker married I00029 in 1723."},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"I00030","display_label":"Brother-in-law via Hart-Hooker triple marriage, 1719-1726","link_text":"Matthew Hart","notes":"One of the three Hart-Hooker marriages between 1719 and 1726: three daughters of Hon. John Hooker (H00030) married three sons of Capt. John Hart (X00033). Matthew Hart married Mary Hooker's sister Sarah Hooker (H00101) in 1726; Mary Hooker married I00029 in 1723."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"She and her sisters all married Hart brothers","body":"She was one of three daughters of John Hooker Esq. of Farmington who each married a son of Capt. John Hart — Abigail to Nathaniel, Mary to Samuel, and Sarah to Matthew — between 1719 and 1725, uniting the two most prominent families of Farmington's founding generation."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Mary Hooker Hart","first_name":"Mary","last_name":"Hart","married_names":["Hart"],"maiden_name":"Hooker"},"landmarks":[],"residence":{"city":"Worthington Parish (now Berlin)","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"mary-hart-1700"},"X00033":{"id":"X00033","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":true},"birth":{"year":1655,"month":1,"day":1,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1714,"month":11,"day":11,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"X01887","mother_id":"X01716","notes":"Son of John Hart (X01887) who perished in the 1666 fire"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X00032","location_city":"Farmington","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_spouse","children_ids":["I00028","I00029","I00030","X00031"]}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entries 99-101 narrative"}],"gender":"male","tags":["politician"],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Hartford founding Hart family"},"cross_connections":[{"type":"in_law","related_id":"H00099","display_label":"married his son Nathaniel in 1719"}],"baptism":{"year":1655,"month":4,"day":2,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM004","plot_notes":"Memento Mori Cemetery, Farmington CT. FindAGrave Memorial ID: 77180356."},"bio":{"display_name":"Captain John Hart","first_name":"John","last_name":"Hart","title":"Captain","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Away tending stock the night his family died","body":"In December 1666 a fire set to the Hart house in Farmington killed everyone inside; John, then about eleven, survived only because he had been sent that night to Nod to tend the family's stock. He grew up the sole survivor of his household."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Three grandsons wed three of Hooker’s granddaughters","body":"John's grandfather, Deacon Stephen Hart, had served Rev. Thomas Hooker's own church in Hartford. A generation later, three of John's grandsons — the brothers Matthew, Samuel, and Nathaniel Hart — married three granddaughters of Thomas Hooker, knotting the two families together within a few years."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"His grandfather’s will singled the orphan out","body":"When Deacon Stephen Hart wrote his will in 1682, he named the fire's lone survivor directly as his eldest son's son. The boy who had lost everyone kept his place in the family record and a small legacy."}],"slug":"john-hart-1655"},"X00032":{"id":"X00032","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1738,"month":9,"day":19,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00033","children_ids":["I00028","I00029","I00030","X00031"],"marriage_number":1}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entries 99-101"}],"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[{"type":"founding_family_nexus","related_id":"I00031","display_label":"Their families united — three sons married three Hooker daughters.","link_text":"Abigail Standley Hooker"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Mary Moore Hart","first_name":"Mary","last_name":"Hart","married_names":["Hart"],"maiden_name":"Moore"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"mary-moore"},"H00030":{"id":"H00030","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":3,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1664,"month":2,"day":20,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1746,"month":2,"day":21,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00007","mother_id":"I00006"},"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 30"},{"short":"Native Northeast Portal","url":"https://www.nativenortheastportal.com/bio/bibliography/hooker-john-1664-1746"},{"short":"L.J. Hooker 1898","full":"L.J. Hooker, 'Edward Hooker, Commander, U.S. Navy,' The Old Northwest Genealogical Quarterly (Columbus, Ohio, 1898-), VII, 12"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00031","children_ids":["H00095","H00096","H00097","H00098","H00099","H00100","H00101","H00102","H00103","H00104"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1687,"date_month":11,"date_day":24}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","notes":"Col. Wadsworth's son Daniel Wadsworth founded the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford — a monument with Hooker family kinship interest. Research needed to confirm Mehitable Russell's Hooker descent line. Warren 1887 confirms: Elizabeth Standley married John Wadsworth — their son Daniel Wadsworth founded the Wadsworth Atheneum.","related_id":"X00035","display_label":"was his father-in-law, honored in the Indian wars","link_text":"Capt. John Standley"},{"type":"civic_peer","notes":"Capt. Thomas Hart b. ca. 1644, d. Aug 27, 1726 age 82. Son of Stephen Hart (X00034). Brother of John Hart who survived the 1666 fire (X00033). Not in this tree through marriage — noted as civic context only.","related_id":"X00034","display_label":"helped govern Farmington alongside him for decades","link_text":"Stephen Hart"},{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"T00387","display_label":"married a descendant of both Hooker and Standley","link_text":"Col. Jeremiah Wadsworth"},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"X00418","display_label":"served Hartford’s founding-family public life alongside him","link_text":"Rev. Daniel Wadsworth"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"X00453","display_label":"was his wife’s sister and Col. Jeremiah Wadsworth’s grandmother","link_text":"Elizabeth Standley"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"X00031","display_label":"fathered four children who married four of his own","link_text":"Capt. John Hart"},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"I00053","display_label":"Both served as Connecticut Colony Supreme Court judges.","link_text":"Hon. Daniel Edwards"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H00089","display_label":"was the cousin whose Indian Neck deed he registered","link_text":"William Hooker"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"X00263","display_label":"signed a Tunxis dispossession deed as his descendant’s in-law","link_text":"Lt. John Mix"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H00439","display_label":"shared his entanglement in Tunxis affairs, decades apart","link_text":"Ezekiel Cowles Jr."},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"X00045","display_label":"was called with him one of Farmington’s two prominent men","link_text":"Captain Thomas Hart"}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM004","plot_notes":"Memento Mori Cemetery, Farmington, Hartford County, Connecticut. Same cemetery as his father Rev. Samuel Hooker (H00007)."},"gender":"male","tags":["politician","judge","compiler_ancestor"],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Connecticut Superior Court judge, 1724-1732","primary_url":"https://www.nativenortheastportal.com/bio/bibliography/hooker-john-1664-1746","primary_url_label":"Native Northeast Portal — John Hooker biography"},"documents":["DOC004"],"residence":{"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"law","header":"Judge of Connecticut Colony's Supreme Court","body":"He served as Judge of the Supreme Court of Connecticut Colony from 1724 to 1732 and as Speaker of the Lower House. He also served as witness, certifying Assistant, and Registrar in the 1733 Sue Squa land deed — three official roles in a single transaction."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"He defended Tunxis land rights in court","body":"In 1738, John Hooker provided a formal statement to the Connecticut General Court that ninety acres at Indian Neck had 'always belonged' to the Tunxis tribe — an unusual act of testimony on behalf of the indigenous people whose land his own ancestors had settled near."},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"The elm fell so someone could walk straight","body":"His father gave him a site on the west side of Farmington's main street, where he built under the branches of a great elm. The tree became famous through all the region for the company that gathered beneath it — three generations of Hookers lived in its shade before a later owner cut it down to straighten the sidewalk."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"The bell tolled — Hooker stepped out first","body":"A chronicler recorded that every Sunday the bell rang, then began tolling; at the first stroke, Hooker issued from his house and proceeded to the Meeting House. The minister walked from his house. Whoever arrived first waited at the door; together they entered — at which the bell stopped and all the congregation arose."},{"number":5,"category":"character","header":"The Sabbath ended when Hooker touched his gate","body":"The holiness of Sunday was supposed to end at sunset — but no child in the town dared stir until John Hooker gave the signal. When the sun sank, he walked to his gate and leaned on it; open flew the doors and out came the children with a wild rush and shout."},{"number":6,"category":"character","header":"Dark hair, dark eyes — dignity commanding respect","body":"His grandson described him: \"Dark hair and dark eyes, and a dignity in his air and expression that procured profound respect.\" A fine looking man, tall, very erect, and had a prominent large nose. He lived his entire life in Farmington, dying there in 1746 at age 81."}],"career":[{"role":"Justice and Register","organization":"Farmington, Connecticut","notes":"Served as justice and register of Farmington"},{"role":"Representative","organization":"Connecticut General Court","notes":"From Farmington. Served as Clerk two sessions; Speaker six sessions."},{"role":"Speaker","organization":"Connecticut General Court Lower House"},{"role":"Assistant","organization":"Colony of Connecticut"},{"role":"Judge, Superior Court","organization":"Colony of Connecticut","notes":"Served as judge of Superior Court concurrent with assistant role"},{"role":"Commissioner, Mohegan Sequestered Land","organization":"New London, Connecticut","notes":"Commissioner of the Mohegan's sequestered land at New London"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Hon. John Hooker","title":"Honorable","first_name":"John","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":[]},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"john-hooker-1664"},"I00031":{"id":"I00031","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1669,"month":7,"day":25,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1743,"month":2,"day":21,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H00030","children_ids":["H00095","H00096","H00097","H00098","H00099","H00100","H00101","H00102","H00103","H00104"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1687,"date_month":11,"date_day":24,"location_country":"United States"}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entries 99-101"}],"parents":{"father_id":"X00035","mother_id":"X00036"},"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_marriage","related_id":"I00051","display_label":"Both married Hooker brothers — from two separate Stanley families.","link_text":"Mary Standley"},{"type":"founding_family_nexus","related_id":"X00032","display_label":"Their families united — three daughters married Hart brothers.","link_text":"Mary Moore Hart"},{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"X00453","display_label":"Her sister Elizabeth Standley married into the Wadsworth line.","link_text":"Elizabeth Standley"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Her father won distinction in the Indian wars","body":"Capt. John Standley was a man of wealth and high social position who had served as lieutenant and captain in the Indian wars. Her sister Elizabeth Standley's granddaughter married Col. Jeremiah Wadsworth, Commissary General of the Continental Army — Wadsworth's wife also descended from Rev. Thomas Hooker, making Wadsworth's children doubly connected to the Hooker line."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Abigail Standley Hooker","notes":"Also spelled 'Stanley' in EH entry 30; 'Standley' in entries 99-101","first_name":"Abigail","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":["Hooker"],"maiden_name":"Standley"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM004","plot_notes":"Memento Mori Cemetery, Farmington CT. SOURCE: FindAGrave."},"slug":"abigail-standley-1669"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}